[src:garnet-cache/in-memory-database] An **in-memory database** (**IMDb**, or **main memory database system** (**MMDB**) or **memory resident database**) is a database management system that primarily relies on main memory for computer data storage.
[src:garnet-cache/in-memory-database] It is contrasted with database management systems that employ a disk storage mechanism.
[src:garnet-cache/in-memory-database] In-memory databases are faster than disk-optimized databases because disk access is slower than memory access and the internal optimization algorithms are simpler and execute fewer CPU instructions.
[src:garnet-cache/in-memory-database] Accessing data in memory eliminates seek time when querying the data, which provides faster and more predictable performance than disk.
[src:garnet-cache/in-memory-database] Applications where response time is critical, such as those running telecommunications network equipment and mobile advertising networks, often use main-memory databases.
[src:garnet-cache/in-memory-database] IMDBs have gained much traction, especially in the data analytics space, starting in the mid-2000s – mainly due to multi-core processors that can address large memory and due to less expensive RAM.
[src:garnet-cache/in-memory-database] A potential technical hurdle with in-memory data storage is the volatility of RAM.
[src:garnet-cache/in-memory-database] Specifically in the event of a power loss, intentional or otherwise, data stored in volatile RAM is lost.
[src:garnet-cache/in-memory-database] With the introduction of non-volatile random-access memory technology, in-memory databases will be able to run at full speed and maintain data in the event of power failure.
[src:garnet-cache/in-memory-database] In its simplest form, main memory databases store data on volatile memory devices.
[src:garnet-cache/in-memory-database] These devices lose all stored information when the device loses power or is reset.
[src:garnet-cache/in-memory-database] In this case, IMDBs can be said to lack support for the "durability" portion of the ACID (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) properties.
[src:garnet-cache/in-memory-database] Volatile memory-based IMDBs can, and often do, support the other three ACID properties of atomicity, consistency and isolation.
[src:garnet-cache/in-memory-database] While storing data in-memory confers performance advantages, it is an expensive method of data storage.
[src:garnet-cache/in-memory-database] An approach to realising the benefits of in-memory storage while limiting its costs is to store the most frequently accessed data in-memory and the rest on disk.
[src:garnet-cache/in-memory-database] Since there is no hard distinction between which data should be stored in-memory and which should be stored on disk, some systems dynamically update where data is stored based on the data's usage.
[src:garnet-cache/in-memory-database] This approach is subtly different from caching, in which the most *recently accessed* data is cached, as opposed to the most *frequently accessed* data being stored in-memory.
[src:garnet-cache/in-memory-database] In the cloud computing industry the terms "data temperature", or "hot data" and "cold data" have emerged to describe how data is stored in this respect.
[src:garnet-cache/in-memory-database] Hot data is used to describe mission-critical data that needs to be accessed frequently while cold data describes data that is needed less often and less urgently, such as data kept for archiving or auditing purposes.
[src:garnet-cache/in-memory-database] Hot data should be stored in ways offering fast retrieval and modification, often accomplished by in-memory storage but not always.
[src:garnet-cache/in-memory-database] Cold data on the other hand can be stored in a more cost-effective way and is accepted that data access will likely be slower compared to hot data.
[src:garnet-cache/in-memory-database] While these descriptions are useful, "hot" and "cold" lack concrete definitions.
[src:garnet-cache/in-memory-database] Manufacturing efficiency provides another reason for selecting a combined in-memory/on-disk database system.
[src:garnet-cache/in-memory-database] Some device product lines, especially in consumer electronics, include some units with permanent storage, and others that rely on memory for storage (set-top boxes, for example).
[src:garnet-cache/in-memory-database] If such devices require a database system, a manufacturer can adopt a hybrid database system at lower and *upper* cost, and with less customization of code, rather than using separate in-memory and on-disk databases, respectively, for its disk-less and disk-based products.
[src:garnet-cache/in-memory-database] The first database engine to support both in-memory and on-disk tables in a single database, WebDNA, was released in 1995.
[src:garnet-cache/in-memory-database] Another variation involves large amounts of nonvolatile memory in the server, for example, flash memory chips as addressable memory rather than structured as disk arrays.
[src:garnet-cache/in-memory-database] A database in this form of memory combines very fast access speed with persistence over reboots and power losses.
[src:garnet-cache/main-readme-md] This repo contains the code to build and run Garnet.
[src:garnet-cache/main-readme-md] For more information and documentation, check out our website at https://microsoft.github.io/garnet.
[src:garnet-cache/main-readme-md] Garnet implements a wide range of APIs including raw strings (e.g., gets, sets, and key expiration), analytical (e.g., HyperLogLog and Bitmap), and object (e.g., sorted sets and lists) operations.
[src:garnet-cache/main-readme-md] It can handle multi-key transactions in the form of client-side RESP transactions and our own server-side stored procedures and modules in C#.
[src:garnet-cache/main-readme-md] It allows users to define custom operations on both raw strings and custom object types, all in the convenience and safety of C#, leading to a lower bar for developing custom extensions.
[src:garnet-cache/main-readme-md] Garnet uses a fast and pluggable network layer, enabling future extensions such as leveraging kernel-bypass stacks.
[src:garnet-cache/main-readme-md] It supports secure transport layer security (TLS) communications using the robust SslStream library of .NET, as well as basic access control.
[src:garnet-cache/main-readme-md] Finally, Garnet supports a cluster mode of operation with support for sharding, replication, and dynamic key migration.
[src:garnet-cache/main-readme-md] We illustrate a few key results on our website comparing Garnet to leading open-source cache-stores.
[src:garnet-cache/main-readme-md] Garnet’s design re-thinks the entire cache-store stack – from receiving packets on the network, to parsing and processing database operations, to performing storage interactions.
[src:garnet-cache/main-readme-md] We build on top of years of our prior research.
[src:garnet-cache/main-readme-md] Garnet’s network layer is based on a shared memory design, with TLS processing and storage interactions performed on the network IO completion thread, avoiding thread switching overheads in the common case.
[src:garnet-cache/main-readme-md] This approach allows CPU cache coherence to bring the data to the processing logic, instead of traditional shuffle-based network designs, which require data movement to the appropriate shard on the server.
[src:garnet-cache/main-readme-md] Garnet’s storage design consists of two Tsavorite key-value stores whose fates are bound by a unified operation log.
[src:garnet-cache/main-readme-md] The first store, called the “main store,” is optimized for raw string operations and manages memory carefully to avoid garbage collection.
[src:garnet-cache/main-readme-md] The second, and optional, “object store” is optimized for complex objects and custom data types, including popular types such as Sorted Set, Set, Hash, List, and Geo.
[src:garnet-cache/main-readme-md] Data types in the object store leverage the .NET library ecosystem for their current implementations.
[src:garnet-cache/main-readme-md] They are stored on the heap in memory (which makes updates very efficient) and in a serialized form on disk.
[src:garnet-cache/main-readme-md] In the future, we plan to investigate using a unified index and log to ease maintenance.
[src:garnet-cache/main-readme-md] A distinguishing feature of Garnet’s design is its narrow-waist Tsavorite storage API, which is used to implement the large, rich, and extensible RESP API surface on top.
[src:garnet-cache/main-readme-md] This API consists of read, upsert, delete, and atomic read-modify-write operations, implemented with asynchronous callbacks for Garnet to interject logic at various points during each operation.
[src:garnet-cache/main-readme-md] Our storage API model allows us to cleanly separate Garnet’s parsing and query processing concerns from storage details such as concurrency, storage tiering, and checkpointing.
[src:garnet-cache/main-readme-md] Garnet uses two-phase locking for multi-key transactions.
[src:garnet-cache/main-readme-md] In addition to single-node execution, Garnet has a fully-featured cluster mode, which allows users to create and manage a sharded and replicated deployment.
[src:garnet-cache/main-readme-md] Garnet also supports an efficient and dynamic key migration scheme to rebalance shards.
[src:garnet-cache/main-readme-md] Users can use standard Redis cluster commands to create and manage Garnet clusters, and nodes perform gossip to share and evolve cluster state.
[src:garnet-cache/main-readme-md] Garnet's cluster mode design is currently *passive*: this means that it does not implement leader election, and simply responds to cluster commands issued by a user-provided *control plane*; see this link for details.
[src:garnet-cache/main-readme-md] Head over to our documentation site, or jump directly to the getting started or releases section.
