[src:garnet-cache/microsoft-research] Between 2010 and 2018, 154,000 AI patents were filed worldwide, with Microsoft having the largest percentage of those patents, at 20%.
[src:garnet-cache/microsoft-research] According to estimates in trade publications, Microsoft spent about $6 billion annually in research initiatives from 2002 to 2010 and has spent from $10–14 billion annually since 2010.
[src:garnet-cache/microsoft-research] Microsoft Research has made significant advances in the field of AI which it has infused in its products including Kinect, Bing, HoloLens, Cortana, Microsoft Translator, LinkedIn, Havok and Dynamics.
[src:garnet-cache/microsoft-research] Microsoft Research includes the core Microsoft Research labs and Microsoft Research AI, Microsoft Research NExT (for New Experiences and Technologies), and other incubation efforts all directed by corporate vice president Peter Lee.
[src:garnet-cache/microsoft-research] Microsoft Research sponsors several research fellowships for faculty and graduate students in the field of computer science.
[src:garnet-cache/microsoft-research] Since 2016, Microsoft has partnered with Toyota Connected to research technology for telematics, data analytics and network security services.
[src:garnet-cache/microsoft-research] In October 2019, Microsoft partnered with Novartis to apply artificial intelligence to enhance personalized medicine research.
[src:garnet-cache/microsoft-research] In 2023, Microsoft signed a multi-year deal to collaborate with Syneos Health in development of a platform to leverage machine learning for the optimization of clinical trials.
[src:garnet-cache/microsoft-research] Microsoft's "AI for Good" initiative represents a significant commitment to leveraging artificial intelligence technology for social and environmental benefits.
[src:garnet-cache/microsoft-research] This initiative is part of a broader vision by Microsoft to utilize AI in addressing some of the world's most challenging issues, including those related to health, the environment, accessibility, cultural heritage, and humanitarian action.
[src:garnet-cache/microsoft-research] AI for Good includes topics like Microsoft AI for Earth.
[src:garnet-cache/microsoft-research] Microsoft Azure Quantum has researched quantum information science since 2000 and is developing a topological quantum computer based on Majorana zero modes.
[src:garnet-cache/microsoft-research] In 2000, physicist Alexei Kitaev at Microsoft Research proposed developing a topological quantum computer from Majorana quasiparticles.
[src:garnet-cache/microsoft-research] In 2002, Michael Freedman, who led Microsoft's quantum research at Station Q in 2005, authored a paper with Kitaev demonstrating how a topological quantum computer could perform any computation that a conventional quantum computer could.
[src:garnet-cache/microsoft-research] In 2005, 2006 and 2008, Sankar Das Sarma, Freedman and Chetan Nayak developed theoretical proposals for a topological qubit using the fractional quantum Hall effect and for topological quantum computing based on non-abelian anyons.
[src:garnet-cache/microsoft-research] In 2015, Microsoft developed the theoretical framework of Majorana zero modes for information processing through braiding-based topological quantum computing.
[src:garnet-cache/microsoft-research] In 2023, Microsoft research demonstrated the creation and control of Majorana quasiparticles for topological quantum computing.
[src:garnet-cache/microsoft-research] In 2024, Microsoft created 4 logical qubits from 30 physical qubits, demonstrating reliable logical qubits by reducing the logical error rate by 800x compared to the physical error rate.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] The project was developed and maintained by Salvatore Sanfilippo, starting in 2009.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] From 2015 until 2020, he led a project core team sponsored by Redis Labs.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] Salvatore Sanfilippo left Redis as the maintainer in 2020.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] In 2021 Redis Labs dropped the Labs from its name and now is known simply as "Redis".
[src:garnet-cache/redis] In 2018, some modules for Redis adopted a modified Apache 2.0 license with a Commons Clause.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] In 2024, the main Redis code switched from the open-source BSD-3 license to being dual-licensed under the Redis Source Available License v2 and the Server Side Public License v1.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] On May 1, 2025, Redis became tri-licensed beginning with version 8.0, with the GNU Affero General Public License as the third option.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] The name *Redis* means Remote Dictionary Server.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] The Redis project began when Salvatore Sanfilippo (nicknamed *antirez*) was trying to improve the scalability of his Italian startup and developed a real-time web log analyzer.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] After encountering significant problems in scaling some types of workloads using traditional database systems, Sanfilippo began in 2009 to prototype a first proof of concept version of Redis in Tcl.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] Later, Sanfilippo translated that prototype to the C language and implemented the first data type, the list.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] After a few weeks of using the project internally with success, Sanfilippo decided to open source it, announcing the project on Hacker News.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] The project began to get traction, particularly among the Ruby community, with GitHub and Instagram being among the first companies adopting it.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] Sanfilippo was hired by VMware in March 2010.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] In May 2013, Redis was sponsored by Pivotal Software (a VMware spin-off).
[src:garnet-cache/redis] In June 2015, development became sponsored by Redis Ltd.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] This made the modules source-available and no longer free software.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] The core Redis software remained under a BSD license, with Redis Ltd. committing to maintaining these terms.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] In October 2018, Redis 5.0 was released, introducing Redis Stream – a new data structure that allows storage of multiple fields and string values with an automatic, time-based sequence at a single key.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] In June 2020, Salvatore Sanfilippo stepped down as Redis' sole maintainer.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] Sanfilippo was succeeded by Yossi Gottlieb and Oran Agra.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] In March 2024, Redis Ltd. announced that beginning with version 7.4, the core Redis software would be relicensed under the RSAL and Server Side Public License (SSPL), both of which are source-available and non-free.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] The Linux Foundation subsequently announced that it would fork the last BSD-licensed version of Redis as Valkey.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] In May 2025, Redis Ltd. announced that it would change the license again to the AGPL beginning on version 8.0, citing that forks had achieved their goal of creating a "level playing field" of differentiated products, and that Redis has achieved "record growth" since the change in license.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] Sanfilippo returned to Redis in December 2024.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] Redis is a system that functions as both a data store and a cache.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] Data is modified and read from the main computer memory while also being persisted to disk in a format optimized for sequential access rather than random access.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] The formatted data is only reconstructed into memory once the system restarts.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] Redis uses a data model that differs from relational database management system (RDBMS).
[src:garnet-cache/redis] Commands specify operations on abstract data types rather than queries to be executed by a database engine.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] Data is stored in structures designed for direct retrieval.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] It does not rely on secondary indexes, aggregations, or other features common in traditional RDBMS.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] The Redis implementation uses the fork system call to duplicate the process holding the data.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] This allows the parent process to continue serving clients while the child process persists the in-memory data to disk.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] Redis supports a number of data types including Strings, JavaScript Object Notation (JSON) documents, Hashes (a collection of fields, each field is a name-value string pair), lists, sets, vector sets, and more.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] The Redis Query Engine allows users to use Redis as a document database, a vector database, a secondary index, and a search engine.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] With Redis Query Engine, users can define indexes for hash and JSON documents, and use a rich query language for vector search, full-text search, geospatial queries, and aggregations.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] Redis Pub/Sub (short for publish/subscribe) is a lightweight messaging capability.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] Publishers send messages to a channel, and subscribers receive messages from that channel.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] A Redis transaction allows the execution of a group of commands in a single step.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] A request sent by another client will never be served during the execution of a transaction.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] This guarantees that the commands are executed as a single isolated operation.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] Redis users can also upload and execute Lua scripts on the server.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] As of May 1, 2025, for all version of Redis starting with 8.0, all data types are included in the same package and available under the Redis Source Available license v2.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] Previously some data types were separate and therefore available under difference licenses.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] Redis typically holds the whole dataset in memory.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] Versions up to 2.4 could be configured to use what they refer to as virtual memory in which some of the dataset is stored on disk, but this feature is deprecated.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] Redis can rewrite the append-only file in the background to avoid an indefinite growth of the journal.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] Journaling was introduced in version 1.1 and is generally considered the safer approach.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] By default, Redis writes data to a file system at least every two seconds, with more or less robust options available if needed.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] In the case of a complete system failure on default settings, only a few seconds of data will be lost.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] Redis supports master–replica replication.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] Data from any Redis server can replicate to any number of replicas.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] A replica may be a master to another replica.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] This allows Redis to implement a single-rooted replication tree.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] Redis replicas can be configured to accept writes, permitting intentional and unintentional inconsistency between instances.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] The publish–subscribe feature is fully implemented, so a client of a replica may subscribe to a channel and receive a full feed of messages published to the master, anywhere up the replication tree.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] Replication is useful for read (but not write) scalability or data redundancy.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] When the durability of data is not needed, the in-memory nature of Redis allows it to perform well compared to database systems that write every change to disk before considering a transaction committed.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] Redis operates as a single process and is single-threaded or double-threaded when it rewrites the AOF (append-only file).
[src:garnet-cache/redis] Thus, a single Redis instance cannot use parallel execution of tasks such as stored procedures.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] Redis introduced clustering in April 2015 with the release of version 3.0.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] The cluster specification implements a subset of Redis commands: all single-key commands are available, multi-key operations (commands related to unions and intersections) are restricted to keys belonging to the same node, and commands related to database selection operations are unavailable.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] A Redis cluster can scale up to 1,000 nodes, achieve "acceptable" write safety and to continue operations when some nodes fail.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] Redis has been used by Adobe, Airbnb, Amazon, Hulu, OpenAI, Salesforce, Shopify, Tinder, Twitter, and Yahoo.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] Typical use cases of Redis are session caching, full page cache, message queue applications, leaderboards and counting among others.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] The publish–subscribe messaging paradigm allows real-time communication between servers.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] Amazon Web Services offers a managed Redis service called ElastiCache for Redis, Google offers a managed Redis service called Cloud Memorystore, Microsoft offers Azure Cache for Redis in Azure, and Alibaba offers ApsaraDB for Redis in Alibaba Cloud.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] Redis is interfaced with by various libraries.
[src:garnet-cache/redis] For example, POCO C++ Libraries supports interfacing with Redis through its `Poco::Redis` library.
